CommonFields.Title: Highly Conductive Poly(methyl methacrylate) (PMMA)-Reduced Graphene Oxide Composite Prepared by Self-Assembly of PMMA Latex and Graphene Oxide through Electrostatic Interaction
Author: Pham, Viet Hung
Dang, Thanh Truong
Hur, Seung Hyun
Kim, Eui Jung
Chung, Jin Suk
CommonFields.Location:
School of Chemical Engineering and Bioengineering, University of Ulsan, Daehakro 102, Namgu, Ulsan 680-749,
Republic of Korea

Mixing.Description: 875 mL of deionized water and 100 g of MMA were charged into a 2 L flask. The mixture was stirred at 350 rpm and bubbled with nitrogen for 30 min.

Additive.Description: 0.15 g of 2,2′-Azobis (2- methylpropionamidine) dihydrochloride dissolved in 25 mL of deionized water was added to the solution.

Mixing.Description: The polymerization was carried out under stirring for 6 h.

ChooseParameter.Other: PMMA was crushed into a fine powder using a mortar and pestle

MoldingInfo.Description: The PMMA was further compression molded in a hydraulic hot press (Collin Press 200G) to create a PMMA pellet

Scanning_Electron_Microscopy.Description: SEM was used to characterize the morphologies of the PMMA-RGO composite powder and the fresh-fractured cross-section of the PMMA-RGO composite pellets. PMMA-RGO composite powder samples were Pt coated before surface scanning.

Dynamic_Mechanical_Analysis.Description: The dynamic mechanical properties of PMMA-RGO were measured using a dynamic mechanical analyzer in a single cantilever deformation mode at a frequency of 1 Hz. The sample size was 30 × 10 × 2 mm3. The temperature was swept from 0 to 180°C at a rate of 3 °C/min.

Differential_Scanning_Calorimetry.Description: Thermal properties of PMMA-RGO were characterized using a TGA (Q50, TA Instruments) and DSC (Q20, TA Instruments) under a nitrogen atmosphere at a heating rate of 10°C/min.

Thermogravimetric_Analysis.Description: Thermal properties of PMMA-RGO were characterized using a TGA (Q50, TA Instruments) and DSC (Q20, TA Instruments) under a nitrogen atmosphere at a heating rate of 10°C/min.
